# Visual Flow Diagram

[HTTP Request] 
    ↓
[ASP.NET Core Router]
    ↓
[DI Container] ← "I need OrderController"
    ↓
[DI Container] ← "OrderController needs EventHandler<OrderPlacedEvent>"
    ↓
[DI Container checks constraints] ← "OrderPlacedEvent implements IEvent? ✅"
    ↓
[DI Container] ← "Create OrderPlacedEventHandler"
    ↓
[DI Container] ← "OrderPlacedEventHandler needs IOrderRepository"
    ↓
[DI Container] ← "Create OrderRepository"
    ↓
[All dependencies resolved] → Create complete object graph
    ↓
[OrderController instance ready with all dependencies injected]
    ↓
[Execute action method]
    ↓
[Return HTTP response]



# What Happens at Runtime

1. User makes HTTP request → POST /orders
   
2. ASP.NET Core needs to create OrderController
   
3. DI Container sees constructor needs:
   - EventHandler<OrderPlacedEvent>
   - IQueryHandler<GetOrderByIdQuery, OrderDto>
   
4. DI Container looks up registrations:
   - "EventHandler<OrderPlacedEvent> → create OrderPlacedEventHandler"
   - "IQueryHandler<...> → create GetOrderByIdHandler"
   
5. But wait! OrderPlacedEventHandler needs dependencies:
   - IValidator<OrderPlacedEvent>
   - IUnitOfWork
   - IEventPublisher
   - IOrderRepository
   
6. DI Container creates those too (recursively)
   
7. DI Container creates OrderController with all dependencies
   
8. Request executes successfully


# Complete Working Example

// 1. Register in Program.cs
builder.Services.AddScoped<IQueryHandler<GetOrderByIdQuery, OrderDto>, GetOrderByIdHandler>();
builder.Services.AddScoped<IOrderRepository, OrderRepository>();

// 2. Inject in Controller
public class OrderController : ControllerBase
{
    private readonly IQueryHandler<GetOrderByIdQuery, OrderDto> _handler;
    
    public OrderController(IQueryHandler<GetOrderByIdQuery, OrderDto> handler)
    {
        _handler = handler;  // DI injects GetOrderByIdHandler
    }
    
    [HttpGet("orders/{id}")]
    public async Task<IActionResult> GetOrder(Guid id)
    {
        var query = new GetOrderByIdQuery(id);
        var result = await _handler.HandleAsync(query);
        return Ok(result);
    }
}

// 3. When request comes in:
// DI creates: GetOrderByIdHandler(new OrderRepository(dbContext))
// Then creates: OrderController(getOrderByIdHandler)
// All automatic!